# Frontend API response normalization

## Rule
API responses pass through a mapping function that converts them to the frontend domain model before reaching components or store. UI code consumes only the normalized model, not the backend shape.

## Why
Backend shapes evolve (new fields, renamed properties, shape differences between REST and GraphQL, response envelopes). A normalization layer isolates UI from those churns and lets the domain model stay stable.

## Constraints
- Each domain has `mapFromApi` / `mapToApi` functions alongside the domain model.
- RTK Query `transformResponse` or Angular service methods own the normalization; components see only the domain type.
- Null / undefined handling and default values live in the mapper, not in components.
- Mappers are unit-tested with representative backend payloads.

## Examples

### Good (TS)
```ts
type Port = { id: string; name: string; country: string; };

const mapFromApi = (raw: PortApi): Port => ({
  id: raw._id ?? raw.id,
  name: raw.port_name,
  country: raw.country_code.toUpperCase(),
});

useGetPortsQuery(undefined, { selectFromResult: ({ data }) => ({ data: data?.map(mapFromApi) }) });
```

### Bad
```tsx
{ports.map(p => <li>{p._id ? p.port_name : p.name}</li>)}  // UI branching on backend shape
```

